der George W. Bush in the name of security: imprecise language, bureaucratic confusion, secrecy, and the bypassing of procedural and legal norms. While the power and legacy of these tools lasted into the Obama years, reliance on them increased exponentially in the Trump era, both in the fight against terrorism abroad and in battles closer to home. Greenberg discusses how the Trump administration weaponized these tools to separate families at the border, suppress Black Lives Matter protests, and attempt to overturn the 2020 presidential election.Revealing the deeper consequences of the war on terror, Subtle Tools paints a troubling portrait of an increasingly undemocratic America where disinformation, xenophobia, and disdain for the law became the new norm, and where the subtle tools of national security threatened democracy itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAdministrative agencieszUnited StatesxReorganization. 0aExecutive powerzUnited States. 0aLawxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aPolitical culturezUnited States. 0aSeptember 11 Terrorist Attacks, 2001xInfluence. 0aTerrorismxPreventionxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aTerrorismzUnited StatesxPreventionxPolitical aspects. 0aUnited StatesxPolitics and governmenty2017- 0aUnited StatesxPolitics and governmenty2017-. 0aWar on Terrorism, 2001-2009xPolitcal aspects. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh  aAbuse of power.  aAccountability.  aActivism.  aAftermath of the September 11 attacks.  aAircraft.  aAl-Qaeda.  aAssassination.  aAt Best.  aAttempt.  aBallot.  aBy-law.  aCivil service.  aCold War (1985–91).  aComplaint.  aCounter-terrorism.  aCredential.  aCrime.  aDeclaration of war.  aDeference.  aDeferred Action for Childhood Arrival